The '''Single African Air Transport Market''' ('''SAATM''') is a project of the [[African Union]] to create a single market for air transport in Africa. Once completely in force, the single market is supposed to allow significant freedom of air transport in Africa, advancing the AU's {{em|Agenda 2063}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uneca.org/stories/single-african-air-transport-market-launched|title=The Single African Air Transport Market is launched|publisher=[[UN Economic Commission for Africa]]|date=2 May 2018|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref>

Primarily, the goal of the SAATM is to fully implement the 1999 [[Yamoussoukro Decision]]. This means that all participants agree to lift [[market access]] restrictions for airlines, remove [[foreign ownership|restrictions on ownership]], grant each other extended [[Freedoms of the air|air traffic rights]] (first through fifth freedoms, not affecting [[cabotage]] rights), and liberalise flight frequency and capacity limits. Both passenger and [[air cargo|cargo aviation]] are included.<ref name="lexology">{{cite web|url=https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=44fb879c-7a37-4060-8db2-399146747ec0|title=Liberalising aviation in Africa: overview of single air transport market|last=Azinge|first=Craig|publisher=Lexology|date=11 April 2018|url-access=registration|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410233809/https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=44fb879c-7a37-4060-8db2-399146747ec0|archive-date=11 April 2018|deadurl=no}}</ref> It also seeks to harmonise safety and security regulations in aviation, based on [[ICAO]] requirements.<ref name="schlumberger" /> Oversight over the SAATM is exercised by the African Union, its [[Regional Economic Communities]] and dedicated sub-institutions for supervision and dispute settlement.<ref>{{cite document|url=http://www.nepad.org/resource/single-african-air-transport-market|title= The Single African Air Transport Market|format=PDF|publisher=[[NEPAD]]|date=January 2018|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref>

== History ==

The benefit of liberalising air traffic, particularly the [[Freedoms of the air#Fifth freedom|fifth freedom]], was first acknowledged in the Yamoussoukro Declaration of 1988.<ref>{{cite document|url=http://repository.uneca.org/handle/10855/13773|title=Declaration of Yamoussoukro on a new African Air Transport Policy|publisher=UN Economic Commission for Africa|format=PDF|date=October 1988|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref> This declaration was reaffirmed in 1999, when the African Union passed the [[Yamoussoukro Decision]].<ref name="schlumberger">{{cite book|url=http://pubdocs.worldbank.org/en/849021434746549856/Air-Transport-OpenSkiesForAfrica.pdf|title=Open Skies for Africa – Implementing the Yamoussoukro Decision|last=Schlumberger|first=Charles E.|publisher=[[The World Bank]]|location=Washington, D.C.|date=2010|isbn=978-0-8213-8205-9}}</ref> However, the implementation of the decision faced obstacles, as regulatory bodies did not become operational as stipulated in the agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.internationallawoffice.com/Newsletters/Aviation/International/George-Etomi-Partners/Liberalising-aviation-in-Africa-the-Yamoussoukro-Decision|title=Liberalising aviation in Africa: the Yamoussoukro Decision|last=Momoh|first=Oshokha Michael|publisher=International Law Office|url-access=registration|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220023421/https://www.internationallawoffice.com/Newsletters/Aviation/International/George-Etomi-Partners/Liberalising-aviation-in-Africa-the-Yamoussoukro-Decision|archive-date=20 February 2018|dead-url=no}}</ref> A number of countries, in an effort of protectionism, refused to grant fifth freedom rights to foreign airlines.<ref name="schlumberger" />

In 2015, the {{em|Declaration for the Establishment of a Single African Air Transport Market}} laid the framework for a single market implementing the Yamoussoukro Decision to be established by 2017.<ref name="lexology" /> This deadline was later extended with plans to launch the single market during the 30th African Union Summit in [[Addis Ababa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tralac.org/news/article/12254-establishment-of-a-single-african-air-transport-market-ministerial-working-group-experts-meeting.html|title=Establishment of a Single African Air Transport Market: Ministerial Working Group Experts’ meeting|website=tralac.org|date=12 October 2017|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref> There, the launch of the SAATM was then made official on 28 January 2018 by Rwandan President [[Paul Kagame]], as new [[Chairperson of the African Union]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/01/31/africa/african-union-single-air-airline/index.html|title=Sky's the limit as Africa makes major move towards aviation single market|last=Giles|first=Chris|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=31 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/4e672998-03f0-11e8-9650-9c0ad2d7c5b5|title=Twenty-three African states launch single aviation market|last=Aglionby|first=John|publisher=[[Financial Times]]|location=Addis Ababa|url-access=limited|date=28 January 2018}}</ref>

== Participation ==

Twenty-three member states of the African Union have agreed to join the SAATM as starting participants.<ref name="quartz">{{cite news|url=https://qz.com/1191558/africa-union-launches-single-african-air-transport-market/|title=African countries have taken the first major step towards cheaper continental flights|last=Kazeem|first=Yomi|publisher=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz Africa]]|date=29 January 2018|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>

