== Evaluation ==

Some African governments and airlines have criticised the project. Especially smaller airlines, as well as the Ugandan government, allege that the agreement would lead to few big airlines dominating the market, thus stifling competition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/air-transport/2018-01-30/africans-still-divided-single-air-transport-market|title=Africans Still Divided on Single Air Transport Market|last=Bekele|first=Kaleyesus|publisher=[[Aviation International News]]|date=30 January 2018|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref>

The [[African Development Bank]], among other analysts, predicted that the SAATM would lead to cheaper flights, greater passenger volumes and economic benefits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.publicfinanceinternational.org/news/2018/04/development-bank-prepares-aviation-plan-africa|title=Development bank prepares aviation plan for Africa|last=Smulian|first=Mark|publisher=PublicFinance International|date=11 April 2018|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref><ref name="schlumberger" />

The [[International Air Transport Association]] commended the African Union for launching the single market, but warned that more work would be required to effectively implement the policy.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.iata.org/pressroom/pr/Pages/2018-01-28-01.aspx|title=IATA Welcomes Single African Air Transport Market but Says Effective Implementation is Key|publisher=[[International Air Transport Association]]|date=28 January 2018|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref>

